00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:05.260
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D. C.

00:00:07.850 --> 00:00:10.910
&gt;&gt; Paolo Bacigalupi is
an award winning writer

00:00:10.910 --> 00:00:14.000
of science fiction and fantasy.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:17.550
His debut novel the "Windup
Girl" shows a vision of humanity

00:00:17.550 --> 00:00:20.050
after being nearly wiped
out by genetic engineering.

00:00:20.050 --> 00:00:25.880
It is chalked full of weird
foods and strange beasts.

00:00:25.880 --> 00:00:30.500
It's one of the top ten
fiction books of 2009 by Time.

00:00:30.500 --> 00:00:36.090
Won the Hugo, Nebula, and John
W. Campbell awards in 2010.

00:00:36.090 --> 00:00:39.150
"Ship Breaker," his
novel published in 2010,

00:00:39.150 --> 00:00:43.460
was award the Michael L. Printz
award for best young adult novel.

00:00:43.460 --> 00:00:45.480
It was nominated for
the National Book Award

00:00:45.480 --> 00:00:47.060
for young people's literature.

00:00:47.060 --> 00:00:51.220
His recent novel the
"Drowned Cities" is a finalist

00:00:51.220 --> 00:00:55.910 position:56%
for the LA Times Book Prize of 2012.

00:00:55.910 --> 00:00:59.800 position:56%
Paolo Bacigalupi has written
fiction for the magazine of "Fantasy

00:00:59.800 --> 00:01:02.690
and Science Fiction" as a
model of science fiction

00:01:02.690 --> 00:01:06.650
and the "Environmental
Journal High County News."

00:01:06.650 --> 00:01:12.120
In an article last
summer on wired.com,

00:01:12.120 --> 00:01:17.900
"How Cyberpunks Saved Science
Fiction" Paolo Bacigalupi wrote

00:01:17.900 --> 00:01:23.180
that science fiction was stuck in
a complacent groove by the 1980s.

00:01:23.180 --> 00:01:26.260
A lazyboy recliner
experience of the future.

00:01:26.260 --> 00:01:30.470
Competent men of science did
competent things aerospace was the

00:01:30.470 --> 00:01:31.810
coolest tech.

00:01:31.810 --> 00:01:36.770
And politics revolved around
the conflicts of nation states.

00:01:36.770 --> 00:01:40.440
Paolo Bacigalupi looks to inspire
and lead a new breed of writers

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:44.400
who looked to touch on raw
issues that interest us all.

00:01:44.400 --> 00:01:47.280
In that vein, "Zombie Baseball
Beatdown" bashes you on the head

00:01:47.280 --> 00:01:50.170
with your very own funny bone.

00:01:50.170 --> 00:01:57.840
Explores raw themes if food
safety, racism, and immigration.

00:01:59.270 --> 00:02:03.220
No. Trying to understand who this
gentleman is he'll certainly tell

00:02:03.220 --> 00:02:04.670
his own story well enough shortly.

00:02:04.670 --> 00:02:05.970
But I did a little looking.

00:02:05.970 --> 00:02:09.650
And I came up across a site
that said that it stems from --

00:02:09.650 --> 00:02:11.670
it was a very old name Bacigalupi

00:02:11.670 --> 00:02:14.480
that goes back to a
Italian mythology.

00:02:14.480 --> 00:02:18.500
Meaning something along the
lines of a kiss of a wolf.

00:02:18.500 --> 00:02:21.310
Although couldn't really
tell if that was true or not.

00:02:21.310 --> 00:02:22.610
There was alternate meaning of it

00:02:22.610 --> 00:02:25.580
that said some person
of dubious integrity.

00:02:25.580 --> 00:02:27.860
So I'll leave that to
all of you to decide.

00:02:27.860 --> 00:02:32.430
But please, join me and welcoming
one of the great emerging writers

00:02:32.430 --> 00:02:35.510
in this genre Paolo Bacigalupi

00:02:35.510 --> 00:02:43.390
[ Applause ]

00:02:43.390 --> 00:02:44.690
&gt;&gt; Thank you [applause].

00:02:44.690 --> 00:02:46.120
I've got a tail with me here so.

00:02:46.120 --> 00:02:49.750
Wow, hi, everybody.

00:02:49.750 --> 00:02:51.530
It's great to see you.

00:02:51.530 --> 00:02:54.890
It's also terrifying to see you.

00:02:54.890 --> 00:02:57.420
Whenever I stand up in
front of people and talk,

00:02:57.420 --> 00:03:00.870
I have this almost immediate
fight or flee reaction.

00:03:00.870 --> 00:03:03.620
And so my first urge just as I
was standing down there was maybe

00:03:03.620 --> 00:03:06.140
if I can just go hide behind here
I'd throw up for a little while.

00:03:06.140 --> 00:03:08.640
I'll be fine.

00:03:08.640 --> 00:03:12.100
But, yeah, thank you very much.

00:03:12.100 --> 00:03:15.600
So as you know now my
name is Paolo Bacigalupi.

00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:18.380
I do write science fiction.

00:03:18.380 --> 00:03:20.600
And I do watch people
sort of immediately sort

00:03:20.600 --> 00:03:22.150
of flinch whenever I say that.

00:03:22.150 --> 00:03:27.850
I've sort of got this sort
of theory about which version

00:03:27.850 --> 00:03:29.400
of literature is most despised.

00:03:29.400 --> 00:03:30.700
Is it romance?

00:03:30.700 --> 00:03:32.100
Is it science fiction?

00:03:32.100 --> 00:03:33.610
Is it children's literature?

00:03:33.610 --> 00:03:35.630
And whichever one it is that
you're sitting next to somebody

00:03:35.630 --> 00:03:36.930 position:56%
and they say, oh, what do you write?

00:03:36.930 --> 00:03:38.230
You say I write science fiction.

00:03:38.230 --> 00:03:39.720
And they go, oh, I don't read that.

00:03:39.720 --> 00:03:41.750
You say, well, that's nice.

00:03:41.750 --> 00:03:43.910
Or you say, oh, well,
I write for children.

00:03:43.910 --> 00:03:46.980
Oh, that's easy writing, right?

00:03:46.980 --> 00:03:49.270
I wish it was easy writing.

00:03:49.270 --> 00:03:53.430
But so -- but I actually write
science fiction for children,

00:03:53.430 --> 00:03:54.990
for young adults, and for adults.

00:03:54.990 --> 00:03:59.390
And I'm really interested in
speaking to different age groups

00:03:59.390 --> 00:04:02.600
because I feel like I
have different stories.

00:04:02.600 --> 00:04:06.200
And i have different ideas
I want to share with people.

00:04:06.200 --> 00:04:08.700
And it's also the most
satisfying thing for me as writer

00:04:08.700 --> 00:04:10.000
because it feels like I get

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:13.820
to stretch different literary
muscles each time I write

00:04:13.820 --> 00:04:16.610
for a different age range.

00:04:16.610 --> 00:04:19.590
So, yeah, so that's kind
of a little bit about me.

00:04:19.590 --> 00:04:25.160
I did actually want to ask you
guys a question because a lot

00:04:25.160 --> 00:04:27.360
of the inspiration for
"Zombie Baseball Beatdown" --

00:04:27.360 --> 00:04:32.640
I still love saying that title.

00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:35.710
Came from the sort of
very specific realization.

00:04:35.710 --> 00:04:41.630
And I just want to ask you all
how many of you have been forced

00:04:41.630 --> 00:04:45.740 position:56%
to read a book that you didn't like?

00:04:47.390 --> 00:04:51.900
How many of you have been forced to
finish a book that you didn't like?

00:04:51.900 --> 00:04:53.620
Right. Okay.

00:04:53.620 --> 00:04:58.930 position:56%
How many of you have been forced to
finish a video game you didn't like?

00:04:58.930 --> 00:05:00.760
We got one [laughter].

00:05:00.760 --> 00:05:04.810
How many of you have been forced

00:05:04.810 --> 00:05:08.770
to finish a TV show
that you didn't like?

00:05:08.770 --> 00:05:10.160
All the way through to the end?

00:05:10.160 --> 00:05:11.770
Yeah, a few.

00:05:11.770 --> 00:05:16.640
Okay. So it's interesting to me
that like when you look at media

00:05:16.640 --> 00:05:18.870
and we look at something like
books and then we look at something

00:05:18.870 --> 00:05:23.050 position:56%
like video games, it's
interesting to me that we've decided

00:05:23.050 --> 00:05:27.150
to turn books into a
medium that's also a misery.

00:05:27.150 --> 00:05:28.850
And I'm not quite sure
why we do that.

00:05:28.850 --> 00:05:31.210
We seem to have some
idea that books,

00:05:31.210 --> 00:05:33.950
even if we're suffering,
it must be good for us.

00:05:33.950 --> 00:05:35.250
It must be worthwhile.

00:05:35.250 --> 00:05:36.550
It must be important.

00:05:36.550 --> 00:05:38.060
In fact, maybe even
the more we suffer,

00:05:38.060 --> 00:05:41.610
the more you know grimy
oatmeal we're forced to shove

00:05:41.610 --> 00:05:43.580
down our throats, the
healthier we'll be

00:05:43.580 --> 00:05:47.350
if we read these good
books that are good for us.

00:05:47.350 --> 00:05:50.870
For me, actually my
experience with this was

00:05:50.870 --> 00:05:54.200
when my stepmother decided I would
not be allowed to read another book

00:05:54.200 --> 00:05:58.250
until I read John Steinbeck's
the "Red Pony."

00:05:59.620 --> 00:06:06.590
And this book for those of
you who haven't read it,

00:06:06.590 --> 00:06:08.890
I'd say don't [brief laughter].

00:06:10.750 --> 00:06:14.200
For me as a kid in middle
school reading this book

00:06:14.200 --> 00:06:15.500
that was good literature --

00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:18.710
my experience of it wasn't that
it was sad or anything like that.

00:06:18.710 --> 00:06:20.700
It was that it was dead boring.

00:06:20.700 --> 00:06:22.450
It was a slog.

00:06:22.450 --> 00:06:24.730
It was a fight to get
through every page.

00:06:24.730 --> 00:06:28.250
The words blurred on the page as I
just waited for the page to turn.

00:06:28.250 --> 00:06:30.170
And I hated that so much.

00:06:30.170 --> 00:06:34.540 position:56%
And it was interesting because at
the same time I was actually reading

00:06:34.540 --> 00:06:35.840
quite a lot.

00:06:35.840 --> 00:06:37.140
But I was reading science fiction.

00:06:37.140 --> 00:06:38.930
I was reading stores
about rocket ships.

00:06:38.930 --> 00:06:41.030
I was reading fantasy
stories about dragons.

00:06:41.030 --> 00:06:44.380
I was reading about great
quest with great swords.

00:06:44.380 --> 00:06:48.310
And there's, you know, something in
here where I was experiencing joy

00:06:48.310 --> 00:06:52.110
in reading in another space
that my stepmother called trash.

00:06:52.110 --> 00:06:55.870
And then she wanted to hand me
something that she's called good.

00:06:55.870 --> 00:06:59.900
And that was where I was
supposed to reside with reading.

00:06:59.900 --> 00:07:04.420
If she had had entire control
over my reading experiences,

00:07:04.420 --> 00:07:06.740
I would not have become a reader.

00:07:06.740 --> 00:07:09.430
And one of the things that
I've noticed in our schooling

00:07:09.430 --> 00:07:12.210
and in the way we treat books
oftentimes is that we know

00:07:12.210 --> 00:07:13.510
which books are good for us.

00:07:13.510 --> 00:07:14.810
And we know which books
are bad for us.

00:07:14.810 --> 00:07:17.020
And never the twain shall meet.

00:07:17.020 --> 00:07:20.760
And that's a fascinating sort
of value set that we apply

00:07:20.760 --> 00:07:24.950
to this specific media more than
any other media that I've seen.

00:07:24.950 --> 00:07:29.130
And when I go and --
so all of that said,

00:07:29.130 --> 00:07:31.660
then my wife is school teacher.

00:07:31.660 --> 00:07:37.550
And she teaches children who are
generally in the range of 4th, 5th,

00:07:37.550 --> 00:07:39.040
and 6th grade, that age group.

00:07:39.040 --> 00:07:43.620
So -- and she has some
kids who hate reading.

00:07:44.710 --> 00:07:47.780
And so one day she said to a couple
of these kids, she says, well,

00:07:47.780 --> 00:07:49.520
what do you want to read about?

00:07:49.520 --> 00:07:50.820
Like, let's start with that.

00:07:50.820 --> 00:07:54.600
And all the kids sort of
look at her and say zombies.

00:07:55.810 --> 00:07:59.490
And sure enough if you go out
and you look at what's available

00:07:59.490 --> 00:08:02.830
for a 4th grader or a 5th grader
or a 6th grader about zombies,

00:08:02.830 --> 00:08:05.390
there's a little bit available
in books about zombies.

00:08:05.390 --> 00:08:07.180
But it's all really cute zombies.

00:08:07.180 --> 00:08:10.270
They're all the, you know, the
zombies that just need a hug.

00:08:10.270 --> 00:08:15.170
They're the zombies that you
can defeat with hot sauce.

00:08:15.170 --> 00:08:17.380
Now, at the same time
that this is going

00:08:17.380 --> 00:08:25.320
on my 9-year-old son is playing an
iPod game called "The Earn to Die."

00:08:25.320 --> 00:08:29.260 position:56%
Where you level up by getting bigger
and bigger vehicles so you can drive

00:08:29.260 --> 00:08:31.150
over more and more zombies.

00:08:31.150 --> 00:08:33.610
And you drive over them
and the zombies splatter

00:08:33.610 --> 00:08:35.010
and blood goes everywhere.

00:08:35.010 --> 00:08:36.480
And, you know, he's driving faster.

00:08:36.480 --> 00:08:38.910 position:56%
And he's laughing the whole sometime
while he's playing this little iPod

00:08:38.910 --> 00:08:41.280
game and driving over zombies.

00:08:41.280 --> 00:08:45.160
And here we got for his age
range in books; you have stories

00:08:45.160 --> 00:08:46.890
about zombies that need a hug.

00:08:46.890 --> 00:08:49.340
But the iPods giving him what he
really wants, which is he wants

00:08:49.340 --> 00:08:52.650
to drive over a bunch of zombies.

00:08:52.650 --> 00:08:57.280
In that moment, I think you have
to look at where your reader is.

00:08:57.280 --> 00:08:59.530
And if you're going to have
somebody become a reader,

00:08:59.530 --> 00:09:01.670
you're going to connect
with their desires.

00:09:01.670 --> 00:09:03.740
You're going to connect
with the things they love.

00:09:03.740 --> 00:09:05.040
You're going to reach
out, and you're going

00:09:05.040 --> 00:09:06.520
to meet them where they want to be.

00:09:06.520 --> 00:09:07.820
You're not going to tell them, no,

00:09:07.820 --> 00:09:10.410
reading is the "Red
Pony" here try this out.

00:09:10.410 --> 00:09:12.360
You're going to say,
you want zombies,

00:09:12.360 --> 00:09:14.440
I'll give you some zombies, kid.

00:09:14.440 --> 00:09:16.910
And that's where I wanted
to be with this book.

00:09:16.910 --> 00:09:22.930
I think that the thing for me
that started me as a reader

00:09:22.930 --> 00:09:28.280
and made me eventually a writer was
that I found that books were joy.

00:09:28.280 --> 00:09:29.630
That books were a pleasure.

00:09:29.630 --> 00:09:30.930
They were excitement.

00:09:30.930 --> 00:09:32.410
They were, you know,
they were getting

00:09:32.410 --> 00:09:34.710
to watch characters do
death defying things.

00:09:34.710 --> 00:09:37.260
With "Zombie Baseball Beatdown"
I wanted to write a story

00:09:37.260 --> 00:09:40.310
where kids got to fight
off the zombie apocalypse.

00:09:40.310 --> 00:09:42.560
Where a bunch of kids
with their baseball bats

00:09:42.560 --> 00:09:50.570
and their teamwork skills were
going to fight the zombie hoard.

00:09:50.570 --> 00:10:01.050
And they were going to
save their small town.

00:10:01.050 --> 00:10:02.350
And I love that feeling.

00:10:02.350 --> 00:10:03.650
That as soon as I started thinking

00:10:03.650 --> 00:10:05.000
about that story I started
getting chills I was

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:06.300
so excited about writing it.

00:10:06.300 --> 00:10:07.600
So I wanted to meet kids
right where they are,

00:10:07.600 --> 00:10:08.900
which is they want
to be entertained.

00:10:08.900 --> 00:10:10.200
They want to be engaged.

00:10:10.200 --> 00:10:11.830
And they want to have a
joyful experience in books.

00:10:11.830 --> 00:10:13.720
They don't hate reading, they hate
the crummy stories we give them

00:10:13.720 --> 00:10:15.020
to read.

00:10:15.020 --> 00:10:16.400
And so I'm going to read just
a small section from this.

00:10:16.400 --> 00:10:17.920
And then I'm going to
talk a little bit more

00:10:17.920 --> 00:10:19.510
about also what else I'm
thinking about writing

00:10:19.510 --> 00:10:20.810
and reading in literature.

00:10:20.810 --> 00:10:23.030
And then after that, assuming
that I don't get a buzz here,

00:10:23.030 --> 00:10:24.330
I'd like to take questions.

00:10:24.330 --> 00:10:25.630
If you guys have any questions.

00:10:25.630 --> 00:10:26.930
So this scene happens
some of the kids --

00:10:26.930 --> 00:10:28.690
when I started thinking
about the zombie apocalypse

00:10:28.690 --> 00:10:30.960
and creating a zombie apocalypse,
one of the questions that came

00:10:30.960 --> 00:10:34.060
up was where was does the
zombie apocalypse come from?

00:10:34.060 --> 00:10:36.910
And for me, the perfect
location for a zombie apocalypse

00:10:36.910 --> 00:10:41.440
to start spreading from was
the local meat packing plant.

00:10:41.440 --> 00:10:43.910
You know, meat handling is a
very, very interesting thing:

00:10:43.910 --> 00:10:46.470
Where our meat comes from;
how our meat gets raised;

00:10:46.470 --> 00:10:47.960
how our meat gets slaughtered.

00:10:47.960 --> 00:10:49.450
It's interesting stuff.

00:10:49.450 --> 00:10:53.400
And there's all sorts of ripe,
you know, opportunities for abuse

00:10:53.400 --> 00:10:54.700
in our meat packing system.

00:10:54.700 --> 00:11:00.090
So this was where I decided to
start my zombie apocalypse from.

00:11:00.090 --> 00:11:03.110
And in this scene, the kids have
snuck into a meat packing plant

00:11:03.110 --> 00:11:07.190
to try to find where the source
of the infection is coming from.

00:11:08.630 --> 00:11:11.940
It's here, Miguel said, standing
in front of some steel doors.

00:11:11.940 --> 00:11:14.190
What is? He didn't answer.

00:11:14.190 --> 00:11:16.120
Just swung the doors open.

00:11:16.120 --> 00:11:18.830
We stood in a cavernous
factory room tangled

00:11:18.830 --> 00:11:20.470
with conveyers and equipment.

00:11:20.470 --> 00:11:23.090
Meat hooks dangled
from chains overhead.

00:11:23.090 --> 00:11:25.400 position:56%
Conveyer belts went every which way.

00:11:25.400 --> 00:11:28.900 position:56%
And massive boxy machines that might
have been grinders or other things,

00:11:28.900 --> 00:11:31.360
but I couldn't tell,
were everywhere.

00:11:31.360 --> 00:11:35.400
The place was so big you couldn't
even see the far side of it.

00:11:35.400 --> 00:11:37.220
We eased into the space.

00:11:37.220 --> 00:11:39.440
It was scary with all the
chains and hooks hanging

00:11:39.440 --> 00:11:41.370
down from their conveyers.

00:11:41.370 --> 00:11:43.640
What are we looking for, Joe asked?

00:11:43.640 --> 00:11:45.400 position:56%
Something that looks zombie, I said.

00:11:45.400 --> 00:11:49.810
Anything. The concrete floors all
glistened with water and blood.

00:11:49.810 --> 00:11:51.380
And everything gleaned.

00:11:51.380 --> 00:11:54.140
It was chilly, and it had
the scent of a meat locker.

00:11:54.140 --> 00:11:56.520 position:56%
It was like smelling life gone cold.

00:11:56.520 --> 00:11:59.110
Our breath steamed in front of us.

00:11:59.110 --> 00:12:00.560
What about the cows, Joe asked?

00:12:00.560 --> 00:12:02.000
Where did they go?

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:04.690
Miguel waved to the far side
of the huge factory floor.

00:12:04.690 --> 00:12:07.960
A bunch of them are in the
next room over in a huge pen.

00:12:07.960 --> 00:12:11.830
The cows get herded up one by one
up a ramp that leads into here.

00:12:11.830 --> 00:12:13.560 position:56%
Suddenly there was a rattling sound.

00:12:13.560 --> 00:12:17.440
Hi. We ducked behind
the conveyer lines.

00:12:17.440 --> 00:12:20.900
Footsteps echoed along with
voices calling out to one another.

00:12:20.900 --> 00:12:23.680
I thought they were all
supposed to be gone, I whispered.

00:12:23.680 --> 00:12:25.910
Another shift, Joe asked?

00:12:25.910 --> 00:12:29.070
No. It's only supposed to be
cleaning crews, Miguel said.

00:12:29.070 --> 00:12:30.480
The guy I talked to
said they were going

00:12:30.480 --> 00:12:31.780
to be cleaning the whole plant.

00:12:31.780 --> 00:12:33.190
So the nightshift wasn't
going to run.

00:12:33.190 --> 00:12:35.100
Just cleaning.

00:12:35.100 --> 00:12:37.040
Lights buzzed and flickered on.

00:12:37.040 --> 00:12:40.130
Workers in white, full body
jump suits streamed in.

00:12:40.130 --> 00:12:42.180
Joe found a spot under
some of the machinery.

00:12:42.180 --> 00:12:43.480
Hide here.

00:12:43.480 --> 00:12:45.260
We just barely squeezed under.

00:12:45.260 --> 00:12:46.950
Don't let your feet stick
out, Miguel whispered.

00:12:46.950 --> 00:12:48.640
They'll see us for sure.

00:12:48.640 --> 00:12:50.730
It was tight but we all fit.

00:12:50.730 --> 00:12:54.970
From our hiding place, we watched
as more and more workers came in.

00:12:54.970 --> 00:12:57.890
Who do those guys remind
you of, I asked?

00:12:57.890 --> 00:13:00.470
Clean up squad, Joe said grimly.

00:13:00.470 --> 00:13:03.490
Yeah, none of these are
regular workers, Miguel said.

00:13:03.490 --> 00:13:06.020
Not with those clothes covering
their whole bodies like that.

00:13:06.020 --> 00:13:08.760
And they don't have aprons
like my uncle and aunt used.

00:13:08.760 --> 00:13:11.810
These have got to be some
other kind of Milrow people.

00:13:11.810 --> 00:13:13.660
The conveyer line started up.

00:13:13.660 --> 00:13:18.190
A door rattled, and suddenly
we could hear cows screaming.

00:13:18.190 --> 00:13:22.650
More workers came in with huge
knives and chain saw like machines.

00:13:22.650 --> 00:13:25.430
They fired them up as
the lines started moving.

00:13:25.430 --> 00:13:26.970
The first cow appeared.

00:13:26.970 --> 00:13:28.360
It had a huge hole in its head.

00:13:28.360 --> 00:13:30.670
But that didn't seem to
bother the cow at all.

00:13:30.670 --> 00:13:31.970
A bunch of hooks snagged it

00:13:31.970 --> 00:13:34.250
and swept it off the
ground as it struggled.

00:13:34.250 --> 00:13:39.230
Moo, the workers went after
it with knives and saws.

00:13:39.230 --> 00:13:41.660
The cow tried to bite
them, but they were fast.

00:13:41.660 --> 00:13:44.070
Cutting and chopping
peeling away the skin.

00:13:44.070 --> 00:13:45.370
The head came off.

00:13:45.370 --> 00:13:46.670
The belly opened up.

00:13:46.670 --> 00:13:47.970
The guts went down the drain.

00:13:47.970 --> 00:13:49.880
The cow's head fell to the floor.

00:13:49.880 --> 00:13:52.200
Moo it said.

00:13:52.200 --> 00:13:55.100
It's hooked body was still jerking
around even without its head.

00:13:55.100 --> 00:13:57.460
A zombie cow for sure, Joe said.

00:13:57.460 --> 00:13:59.740
As if we needed him to tell us.

00:13:59.740 --> 00:14:04.360
The cow was still alive even
though it was completely dead.

00:14:04.360 --> 00:14:06.350
One of the workers got
kicked by the dead cow.

00:14:06.350 --> 00:14:08.910
But he got right up and
chopped the carcass in half.

00:14:08.910 --> 00:14:11.890
Then water sprayed it and the
next worker whacked off the legs.

00:14:11.890 --> 00:14:14.370
The carcass whizzed along
carried by the hooks with more

00:14:14.370 --> 00:14:16.210
and more workers slicing
cuts of meat

00:14:16.210 --> 00:14:19.730
from the body even
as it kept wiggling.

00:14:19.730 --> 00:14:29.600
The cow -- look at the rain --
the zombie cow became smaller

00:14:29.600 --> 00:14:31.900
and smaller and less
and less like a cow

00:14:31.900 --> 00:14:34.070
as each worker took a whack at it.

00:14:34.070 --> 00:14:36.620
Pieces and parts were slashed
and sliced away and dropped

00:14:36.620 --> 00:14:39.740
onto conveyer belts that whisked
the meat this way and that way

00:14:39.740 --> 00:14:41.140
through the processing plant.

00:14:41.140 --> 00:14:43.000
Heading for who knew where.

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:44.870
Another cow entered
the production line.

00:14:44.870 --> 00:14:47.430
And the clean up squad
went up to that too.

00:14:47.430 --> 00:14:54.430
Moo, slice, hack, chop [chain
saw sounds] went the chain saws.

00:14:54.430 --> 00:14:57.160
Another cow whacked
into little red pieces.

00:14:57.160 --> 00:14:58.600
More of the line was gearing.

00:14:58.600 --> 00:15:00.680
It was crazy loud in the
factory now like we were

00:15:00.680 --> 00:15:02.590
in the belly of a clanging monster.

00:15:02.590 --> 00:15:04.870
Ground up meat oozed
out of delivery tubes.

00:15:04.870 --> 00:15:06.420
And newly cut steaks whipped

00:15:06.420 --> 00:15:09.770
down the conveyer lines
shrink wrapped in plastic.

00:15:09.770 --> 00:15:12.120
More and more cows were
being herded into the doors.

00:15:12.120 --> 00:15:14.280
And every single one
of them was mooing even

00:15:14.280 --> 00:15:16.350
after it was chopped up and dead.

00:15:16.350 --> 00:15:18.270
The cow heads that
had been discarded lay

00:15:18.270 --> 00:15:20.400
in a huge pile snapping
at one another.

00:15:20.400 --> 00:15:23.090
And at any workers
who walked past them.

00:15:23.090 --> 00:15:25.130
Pound after pound of
red hamburger poured

00:15:25.130 --> 00:15:26.460
out of the machines around us.

00:15:26.460 --> 00:15:29.320
Globs of beef that dropped
on to Styrofoam plates.

00:15:29.320 --> 00:15:31.680
And then went through shrink
wrapping machines so that they came

00:15:31.680 --> 00:15:34.530
out on the other side
looking shiny and fresh

00:15:34.530 --> 00:15:37.320
with Milrow meat stickers
on the plastic.

00:15:37.320 --> 00:15:39.390
Labels sped past us.

00:15:39.390 --> 00:15:44.150
Farmers Feast 100 percent
all natural ground beef.

00:15:44.150 --> 00:15:47.680
Forest Glen Acres pure ground beef.

00:15:47.680 --> 00:15:52.690
High Plains Ranches USDA
natural ground beef.

00:15:52.690 --> 00:15:55.210
Milrow Meats top quality beef

00:15:55.210 --> 00:15:59.000
from our family ranches
to your family table.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.980
Joe had his cell phone out, and he
was snapping pictures looking sick.

00:16:01.980 --> 00:16:05.910
I think I'm a vegetarian, he said.

00:16:05.910 --> 00:16:07.930
Miguel gave him an annoyed glance.

00:16:07.930 --> 00:16:09.840
Where did you think
your meat came from?

00:16:09.840 --> 00:16:11.140
You think it just [inaudible]

00:16:11.140 --> 00:16:13.000
into the night supermarket
like night crawler?

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:15.640
I had to agree with Joe though.

00:16:15.640 --> 00:16:17.430
It was brutal and nasty.

00:16:17.430 --> 00:16:18.820
None of the workers
seemed to be worried

00:16:18.820 --> 00:16:20.150
about what they were doing at all.

00:16:20.150 --> 00:16:22.370
They were just being
super efficient.

00:16:22.370 --> 00:16:25.550
Even if it hadn't been zombie cow
heads lying on the ground mooing

00:16:25.550 --> 00:16:27.260
and rolling their eyes
and snapping their teeth,

00:16:27.260 --> 00:16:30.020
the whole set up didn't
feel good to watch.

00:16:30.020 --> 00:16:32.840
I mean, I went out to
a farm with my dad once

00:16:32.840 --> 00:16:34.140
where we bought a sheep for mutton.

00:16:34.140 --> 00:16:36.710
And we saw the farmer
kill the sheep.

00:16:36.710 --> 00:16:38.550
He stuck his knife in
the sheep's throat.

00:16:38.550 --> 00:16:40.250
And we watched him kill it.

00:16:40.250 --> 00:16:43.000
And it was uncomfortable
because you could see

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:45.500
that something was dying
so you could eat it.

00:16:45.500 --> 00:16:49.260
But killing a sheep up close
and personal wasn't like this.

00:16:49.260 --> 00:16:50.870
The sheep bled and got chopped up.

00:16:50.870 --> 00:16:52.860
And dad and I ate it, sure.

00:16:52.860 --> 00:16:55.430
But this Milrow factory
was something else.

00:16:55.430 --> 00:16:58.700
Cow after cow coming into the
plant and getting ripped to pieces.

00:16:58.700 --> 00:17:01.690
High speed chopping,
ripping, tearing, shrinking.

00:17:01.690 --> 00:17:04.620
I wondered what kind of people
could create a factory like this.

00:17:04.620 --> 00:17:08.340
All for tearing animals
apart as fast as possible.

00:17:08.340 --> 00:17:10.030
It scared me.

00:17:10.030 --> 00:17:12.600
They're turning all the zombie
cows into food for people, I said.

00:17:12.600 --> 00:17:13.900
I can't believe it.

00:17:13.900 --> 00:17:15.320
They're insane.

00:17:15.320 --> 00:17:16.900
It was all zombie cows.

00:17:16.900 --> 00:17:19.860
Not a single real cow
in the whole bunch.

00:17:19.860 --> 00:17:23.070
So this is what ground zero for
the zombie apocalypse looks like.

00:17:23.070 --> 00:17:24.620
Joe snapped more pictures.

00:17:24.620 --> 00:17:27.930
I sort of thought it would be a
military science lab somewhere.

00:17:27.930 --> 00:17:29.440
We've got to stop this, I said.

00:17:29.440 --> 00:17:31.200
We can't let them do this.

00:17:31.200 --> 00:17:33.300
There's a stop button
on the line, Joe said.

00:17:33.300 --> 00:17:34.740
Miguel whacked him upside the head.

00:17:34.740 --> 00:17:36.140
Not just now, idiot.

00:17:36.140 --> 00:17:37.440
We got to report it.

00:17:37.440 --> 00:17:40.120
We got to make sure
this all gets stopped.

00:17:40.120 --> 00:17:42.790
We need something they can't
sweep under the table, I said.

00:17:42.790 --> 00:17:45.190
Something the cops can't ignore.

00:17:45.190 --> 00:17:47.690
Real zombie proof, Joe murmured.

00:17:47.690 --> 00:17:50.850
Something you just couldn't
make up, Miguel said.

00:17:50.850 --> 00:17:55.760
Moo, moaned the cow heads lying
in a giant pile at the beginning

00:17:55.760 --> 00:17:57.420
of the meat packing line.

00:17:57.420 --> 00:18:02.660
Moo, we all looked at each other.

00:18:02.660 --> 00:18:06.510
A mooing zombie cow head, yeah,
that would probably do the trick.

00:18:06.510 --> 00:18:16.930
[ Applause ]

00:18:16.930 --> 00:18:19.670
All right so I loved
writing this book.

00:18:19.670 --> 00:18:21.570
I had far too much
fun doing this book.

00:18:21.570 --> 00:18:24.510
No one of the things that I
also kind of wanted to talk

00:18:24.510 --> 00:18:29.620
about was the idea that we know
what's good for us in literature.

00:18:29.620 --> 00:18:31.500
And we know what's bad
for us in literature.

00:18:31.500 --> 00:18:32.850
We know what's trashy.

00:18:32.850 --> 00:18:36.120
And we know what's healthy for our
kids to read or for us to read.

00:18:36.120 --> 00:18:39.310
And we separate those things
out in really interesting ways.

00:18:39.310 --> 00:18:43.700
And I'm not sure that I believe
that that's actually the right way

00:18:43.700 --> 00:18:45.240
to think about storytelling.

00:18:45.240 --> 00:18:48.320
I have this feeling that
it's possible for us

00:18:48.320 --> 00:18:50.170
to have our cake and eat it too.

00:18:50.170 --> 00:18:52.710
That we can have all
the joys of running

00:18:52.710 --> 00:18:55.130
around in the pop culture
space of zombies.

00:18:55.130 --> 00:18:58.340
But we can also talk about other
things that are extremely serious.

00:18:58.340 --> 00:19:02.150
The opportunity to talk about
where does our meat come from?

00:19:02.150 --> 00:19:03.450
How do we treat it?

00:19:03.450 --> 00:19:04.750
What do we eat?

00:19:04.750 --> 00:19:06.050
Who's in charge of it?

00:19:06.050 --> 00:19:07.350
How does it get regulated?

00:19:07.350 --> 00:19:08.650
Who protects our food?

00:19:08.650 --> 00:19:10.990
All of those questions
are also in this book.

00:19:10.990 --> 00:19:13.420
And it's one of the things that's a
huge pleasure for me is to be able

00:19:13.420 --> 00:19:15.390
to say I'm going to
tell you a fun story

00:19:15.390 --> 00:19:18.440
about kids beating back the zombie
hoard with their baseball bats.

00:19:18.440 --> 00:19:21.590
Oh, by the way, let's think about
how food works in our country too,

00:19:21.590 --> 00:19:22.890
because that's interesting.

00:19:22.890 --> 00:19:24.400
And I think you can have
both of those things.

00:19:24.400 --> 00:19:26.470
And it can all be a
fun, thrilling package.

00:19:26.470 --> 00:19:29.670
And there's none of this,
like, oh, it sucks to read it.

00:19:29.670 --> 00:19:31.520
This is actually going to
be fun all the way through.

00:19:31.520 --> 00:19:32.820
I get to learn.

00:19:32.820 --> 00:19:34.480
I get to have joy both
at the same time.

00:19:34.480 --> 00:19:36.910
And that's where I think that
sort of literature needs to be.

00:19:36.910 --> 00:19:42.170 position:56%
And that's where unabashedly we know
that almost all other media wants

00:19:42.170 --> 00:19:44.080
to be, is they want
to sort of spread joy.

00:19:44.080 --> 00:19:47.430
They want people to be
engaged and entertained.

00:19:47.430 --> 00:19:50.450
Video games movies, TV
shows, are all trying

00:19:50.450 --> 00:19:52.400
to engage and entertain first.

00:19:52.400 --> 00:19:54.010
Everything else comes second.

00:19:54.010 --> 00:19:56.570
And I think that books have made a
mistake somewhere along the line.

00:19:56.570 --> 00:19:58.730
And definitely our teaching
establishment has made a mistake,

00:19:58.730 --> 00:20:00.050 position:56%
you know, the way we do our testing,

00:20:00.050 --> 00:20:02.450
everything to say no
good for you first.

00:20:02.450 --> 00:20:04.970
Oh, if you have fun, well,
we'll try to accept that.

00:20:04.970 --> 00:20:07.200
But please, you know,
don't have too much fun.

00:20:07.200 --> 00:20:10.240
And I really sort of want to
bring those two ideas together.

00:20:10.240 --> 00:20:11.640
It's like, yeah, we
can think about things.

00:20:11.640 --> 00:20:12.940
We have been thoughts.

00:20:12.940 --> 00:20:14.240
Big themes.

00:20:14.240 --> 00:20:15.980
And also big, big zombie battles.

00:20:15.980 --> 00:20:18.510
So -- thank you.

00:20:18.510 --> 00:20:22.780
[ Applause ]

00:20:22.780 --> 00:20:26.300
So if anybody has any questions
I'd be happy to answer questions.

00:20:26.300 --> 00:20:29.460
I'm happy to talk about
almost anything.

00:20:29.460 --> 00:20:31.880
So feel free and fire away.

00:20:31.880 --> 00:20:34.880
I guess there are microphones
on either side here so.

