00:20:36.180 --> 00:20:44.580
&gt;&gt; Hi, as an educator of teachers,

00:20:44.580 --> 00:20:46.540
I agree with a lot of
what you're saying.

00:20:46.540 --> 00:20:51.090
But I would also ask the question
of how many people have been forced

00:20:51.090 --> 00:20:53.300
to read a book that they
turned out that they loved it?

00:20:53.300 --> 00:20:58.160 position:56%
And that could be the book that
you're talking about, as well as any

00:20:58.160 --> 00:21:00.060
of the other literature
in the world.

00:21:00.060 --> 00:21:03.300
So I think that that's an
important question to ask as well.

00:21:03.300 --> 00:21:04.750
&gt;&gt; It's an interesting
question is --

00:21:04.750 --> 00:21:06.900
the question is sort of how
many people have been forced

00:21:06.900 --> 00:21:09.580
to read a book and then found
that they did love it later?

00:21:09.580 --> 00:21:12.570
And I think that that's possible.

00:21:12.570 --> 00:21:14.750
Certainly I had a teacher
in high school who forced me

00:21:14.750 --> 00:21:16.610
to read Shakespeare for a semester.

00:21:16.610 --> 00:21:19.320
And eventually I did
come to love Shakespeare.

00:21:19.320 --> 00:21:22.760
I was taught to eat the
right kind of food I suppose.

00:21:22.760 --> 00:21:31.100 position:56%
I think though that especially when
we talk about our classic literature

00:21:31.100 --> 00:21:34.820
that we forget how our classic
literature knew that it needed

00:21:34.820 --> 00:21:36.780
to earn it's keep in its time.

00:21:36.780 --> 00:21:40.050
Shakespeare didn't
sit down to say, oh,

00:21:40.050 --> 00:21:41.870
I'm going to force
you to enjoy this.

00:21:41.870 --> 00:21:45.000
He was actually writing
exactly for his popular culture.

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:47.570
And so I feel like there's a --

00:21:47.570 --> 00:21:50.530
we've decided that because
it's hard therefore it's good.

00:21:50.530 --> 00:21:53.510
As opposed to, because it's
enjoyable therefore it's good.

00:21:53.510 --> 00:21:55.430
Because it's engaging
therefore it's good.

00:21:55.430 --> 00:21:58.970
I feel like we've somehow managed
to sort of worship our past enough

00:21:58.970 --> 00:22:01.400
that we've forgotten that our
present is actually what most

00:22:01.400 --> 00:22:03.840
writers -- the reason why
writers are classics now is

00:22:03.840 --> 00:22:06.190
because they were deeply
embedded in their present moment.

00:22:06.190 --> 00:22:09.510
And writing very, very specifically
for their present readers.

00:22:09.510 --> 00:22:12.640
And we sort of managed to separate
that within our educational system.

00:22:12.640 --> 00:22:13.940
I'm not saying that
it can't be done.

00:22:13.940 --> 00:22:16.940
I'm not saying that we can't
be taught to enjoy new things.

00:22:16.940 --> 00:22:21.040
But especially at younger ages,
I think that it's a horrible,

00:22:21.040 --> 00:22:24.370 position:56%
horrible thing to do somebody is to
say, no, no, keep going, keep going,

00:22:24.370 --> 00:22:25.670
keep going and suffering.

00:22:25.670 --> 00:22:27.020
It's like I think you
start with the sweets.

00:22:27.020 --> 00:22:30.150
You assume that -- for me
at least, I think about this

00:22:30.150 --> 00:22:33.140
as being the question of, like,
you assume that if I can get kids

00:22:33.140 --> 00:22:36.730
to start reading and enjoying
reading and loving reading,

00:22:36.730 --> 00:22:39.330
this is not going to be
the last book they read.

00:22:39.330 --> 00:22:40.980
The idea is it's the
first book they read.

00:22:40.980 --> 00:22:44.610 position:56%
And that gets them on a journey that
goes all kinds of different places.

00:22:44.610 --> 00:22:48.260
But if I start out with something
that's horrible and boring

00:22:48.260 --> 00:22:51.570
and difficult and not engaging
and not relevant to me,

00:22:51.570 --> 00:22:53.000
then it will be the last book.

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:54.300
And that's sad.

00:22:54.300 --> 00:22:55.600
And then they -- and the iPods

00:22:55.600 --> 00:22:56.900
and everything else
will take them instead.

00:22:56.900 --> 00:22:59.410
I do think that there's
a point in our lives --

00:22:59.410 --> 00:23:01.510
and for me I didn't
actually read any, you know,

00:23:01.510 --> 00:23:04.590
major what we would call
like quality literature

00:23:04.590 --> 00:23:06.800
until after I was out of college.

00:23:06.800 --> 00:23:08.930
Until then I read science
fiction entirely.

00:23:08.930 --> 00:23:11.400
That was what I read, and
that was what I truly loved.

00:23:11.400 --> 00:23:13.480
And then there was a
point when suddenly I was,

00:23:13.480 --> 00:23:14.780
like, oh, this is interesting.

00:23:14.780 --> 00:23:16.370
You know, Hemingway,
oh, fascinating.

00:23:16.370 --> 00:23:17.670
Oh, "Virginia Wolf."

00:23:17.670 --> 00:23:19.000
Oh, fascinating whatever
those things were.

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:20.330
I was finally ready for that.

00:23:20.330 --> 00:23:22.460
If I had stopped reading
at an earlier stage though,

00:23:22.460 --> 00:23:24.730 position:56%
I would have never even had a
chance to pick up those later books.

00:23:24.730 --> 00:23:27.190
So it's kind of what I think about.

